SIMPLE: revulsion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revulsion
<hw>Re*vul"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧vulsion</ets>, L. <ets>revulsio</ets>, fr.
<ets>revellere</ets>, <ets>revulsum</ets>, to pluck or pull away; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>vellere</ets> to pull. Cf.
<er>Convulse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A strong pulling or drawing
back; withdrawal.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Revulsions</xex> and
pullbacks.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>SSir T. Brovne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sudden reaction; a sudden and complete change; --
applied to the feelings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sudden and violent <qex>revulsion</qex> of feeling, both in the
Parliament and the country, followed.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The act of turning or diverting
any disease from one part of the body to another. It resembles
<xex>derivation</xex>, but is usually applied to a more active form of
counter irritation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revulsive</ent>⟦br⟧
